1. Read / import Level 2 SWOT data

- Read `L2_HR_PIXC` (pixel cloud) for the region and cycles of interest.
- Variables needed: height, σ_phase_noise,
  dh/dφ, geolocation_qual (Q_geo), classification,
  latitude, longitude, azimuth_index, range_index.


2. Compute height anomaly (per cycle)

- Choose a reference open water point, a location that is always open
  water and never intertidal, for the region of interest. Identify it by
  cycle-wise visual inspection of height.
- Select the nearest `L2_HR_PIXC` pixel to that point with Q_geo == 0.
- Compute the median height within a 0.001° buffer around that pixel.
- Subtract this median from every other pixel's height in the region 
  (height anomaly, h_a).
- h_a has a consistent, characteristic pattern over open water
  but a distinctly different one over non water pixels, generally producing
  a bimodal distribution once an intertidal zone is present.


3. Filter with σ_phase_noise threshold (per cycle)

- Remove any pixel with σ_phase_noise above a user defined threshold
  (paper uses ≈0.08 radian, refined per site).
- This mostly strips out land pixels (land/land near water medians exceed
  approximatly 0.2 rad; open water/water near land medians are typically <0.05 rad).
- Initial threshold estimate: median σ_phase_noise across all cycles in the
  region, then tuned empirically.


4. Filter open-water pixels via the height anomaly PDF (per cycle)

- On the remaining σ_phase_noise filtered pixels, compute a Gaussian
  KDE-based PDF of h_a (PDF(h_a)) with an adaptively sized bin count
  (fixed bin width ≈ 5 cm).
- Identify peaks with density ≥ 0.1:
  - Low tide will have two distinct peaks
  - Mid tide will have two overlapping but distinguishable peaks
  - High tide will have a single peak
- Assume the first peak, h_a peak, is open water (may include a small
  fraction of inland water, negligible at low tide).
- Upper cutoff `h_a^upper`: first `h_a > h_a^peak` where `PDF(h_a)`
  drops to ≤ 1% of the peak's density (ε_up).
- Lower cutoff `h_a^lower` (separates open water from non-open-water):
  - Case A — multiple minima in `PDF'(h_a)` within `[h_a^peak, h_a^upper]`
    (typical low/mid tide): find the largest-magnitude minimum
    `h_a^min` and the next local minimum `h_a^next`; set
    `ε_low = |PDF'(h_a^min)| / 50`; take the first `h_a` in
    `[h_a^min, h_a^next]` where `|PDF'(h_a)| ≤ ε_low`, avoiding the
    non-open-water peak position. If it lands on that peak, shrink the
    search interval and repeat.
  - Case B — single minimum in `PDF'(h_a)` (typical high tide): find
    the peak of `PDF''(h_a)` at `h_a^{peak,PDF''}` for `h_a > h_a^min`;
    set `ε_low = min(PDF'(h_a)) / 50` for `h_a > h_a^{peak,PDF''}`; take
    the first `h_a` beyond that point where `|PDF'(h_a)| ≤ ε_low`.
  - In either case, if `h_a^lower ≥ h_a^upper`, double ε_low and repeat
    until `h_a^lower < h_a^upper`.
- Retain only pixels with `h_a` outside `[h_a^lower, h_a^upper]` on the
  open-water side (i.e., `h_a < h_a^lower`) as excluded open water; pixels
  within `[h_a^lower, h_a^upper]` are the candidate non-open-water set
  (intertidal + land).


5a. Build the water extent mask (once per region, using all cycles)

- Create a regular high-resolution grid over the region (e.g., 0.0001°).
- For each available SWOT cycle, build a per-cycle validity grid: cell =
  count of pixels passing the σ_phase_noise threshold (Step 3) within that
  cell.
- Stack and sum validity grids across all cycles.
- Keep only cells above a user-defined quantile of total validity (e.g.,
  90%; lower, e.g. 75%, for geomorphologically complex sites).
- Delineate outlines of the resulting high-validity clusters (buffer
  operation); keep only the largest-area polygon (assumed = open
  water/intertidal extent).
- Clean the polygon: drop small holes below an area/perimeter threshold
  (likely noise, not real islands); smooth with a moving average.
- This produces the water extent mask, computed once and reused for
  every cycle.

5b. Apply the water extent mask (per cycle)

- Take the candidate non-open-water pixels from Step 4.
- Discard any pixel falling outside the water extent mask (these are
  inland/land pixels, not intertidal).
- Remaining pixels = final classified intertidal pixels for that cycle.



6. (Optional) Quality-control refinements

Several known failure modes worth guarding against:
- Reference point accidentally falling in a dark water pixel, biases the
  whole anomaly PDF; check its classification before using it.
- dark water pixels elsewhere in open ocean can create a spurious third
  PDF peak; consider filtering classification == dark water pixels, but
  cautiously (SWOT's own dark-water flag can misfire in dynamic coasts).
- Large ROIs spanning significant tidal/geoid gradients can bias the PDF;
  either shrink the ROI, remove the gradient from `height` first, or use
  multiple sub-zone reference points.
- Missing/unreliable Δh_xover_cor for a cycle, exclude that cycle (see
  Step 0).



7. Estimate per-pixel height uncertainty

For each retained intertidal pixel:

σ_h = |dh/dφ| × σ_phase_noise


8. Aggregate intertidal pixels into a topography grid

- Define an output grid (paper uses ≈0.00025°, ~20 m).
- For each output grid cell containing n intertidal pixels with heights
  h = [h_1, ..., h_n] and uncertainties σ_h = [σ_h1, ..., σ_hn], run a
  Monte Carlo median aggregation (chosen over plain median or weighted
  mean for robustness to outliers + uncertainty-awareness):
  - For i = 1...L realizations: perturb each pixel height with Gaussian
    noise scaled by its own σ_h, take the median of that perturbed set 
    M_i.
  - Final cell height = median of all M_i.
  - 95% confidence interval = the [α, 1−α] quantiles of the sorted `M_i`.
- (Optional) Multi-cycle stacking: repeat aggregation combining pixels
  from multiple low/mid-tide cycles (paper uses 8 low + 8 mid tide cycles)
  to reduce single-cycle interferometric noise — stacked results show
  markedly lower RMSE than single-cycle in the paper's validation.


9. (Optional) Validate output
- Re-grid a reference DEM (e.g., LiDAR) onto the same output grid.
- Compute per-cell height differences (SWOT − reference).
- Report mean/median bias, standard deviation, RMSE — optionally stratified
  by bottom type or local slope, since the paper finds degraded accuracy
  over rocky/steep terrain (layover effects).



